  "docs": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "kind": "summary",
        "title": "Summary",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "Returns True if the type of `element` is a scalar type."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "parameters",
        "title": "Parameters",
        "items": [
          {
            "name": "element",
            "type": "any",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "Input argument, can be of any type and shape."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "returns",
        "title": "Returns",
        "items": [
          {
            "name": "val",
            "type": "bool",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "True if `element` is a scalar type, False if it is not."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "notes",
        "title": "Notes",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "If you need a stricter way to identify a *numerical* scalar, use\n``isinstance(x, numbers.Number)``, as that returns ``False`` for most\nnon-numerical elements such as strings."
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "In most cases ``np.ndim(x) == 0`` should be used instead of this function,\nas that will also return true for 0d arrays. This is how numpy overloads\nfunctions in the style of the ``dx`` arguments to `gradient` and\nthe ``bins`` argument to `histogram`. Some key differences:"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "+------------------------------------+---------------+-------------------+\n| x                                  |``isscalar(x)``|``np.ndim(x) == 0``|\n+====================================+===============+===================+\n| PEP 3141 numeric objects           | ``True``      | ``True``          |\n| (including builtins)               |               |                   |\n+------------------------------------+---------------+-------------------+\n| builtin string and buffer objects  | ``True``      | ``True``          |\n+------------------------------------+---------------+-------------------+\n| other builtin objects, like        | ``False``     | ``True``          |\n| `pathlib.Path`, `Exception`,       |               |                   |\n| the result of `re.compile`         |               |                   |\n+------------------------------------+---------------+-------------------+\n| third-party objects like           | ``False``     | ``True``          |\n| `matplotlib.figure.Figure`         |               |                   |\n+------------------------------------+---------------+-------------------+\n| zero-dimensional numpy arrays      | ``False``     | ``True``          |\n+------------------------------------+---------------+-------------------+\n| other numpy arrays                 | ``False``     | ``False``         |\n+------------------------------------+---------------+-------------------+\n| `list`, `tuple`, and other         | ``False``     | ``False``         |\n| sequence objects                   |               |                   |\n+------------------------------------+---------------+-------------------+"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "examples",
        "title": "Examples",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> import numpy as np"
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> np.isscalar(3.1)\nTrue"
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> np.isscalar(np.array(3.1))\nFalse"
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> np.isscalar([3.1])\nFalse"
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> np.isscalar(False)\nTrue"
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> np.isscalar('numpy')\nTrue"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "NumPy supports PEP 3141 numbers:"
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> from fractions import Fraction\n>>> np.isscalar(Fraction(5, 17))\nTrue\n>>> from numbers import Number\n>>> np.isscalar(Number())\nTrue"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
